24	_DETAILED_HELP_TEXT = ("""
25	<B>OVERVIEW</B>
26	  Cloud SDK includes a new CLI, gcloud storage, that can be considerably faster
27	  than gsutil when performing uploads and downloads with less parameter
28	  tweaking. This new CLI has a syntax and command structure that is familiar to
29	  gsutil users but is fundamentally different in many important ways. To ease
30	  transition to this new CLI, gsutil provides a shim that translates your gsutil
31	  commands to gcloud storage commands if an equivalent exists, and falls back to
32	  gsutil's usual behavior if an equivalent does not exist.
33	                       
34	<B> PREREQUISITES </B>
35	                       
36	You should be running gsutil binary installed via Cloud SDK tool.
37	To verify this, run ``gsutil ver -l`` and you should be able to see
38	``pass cloud sdk credentials to gsutil: True``. If it is ``False``,
39	try running ``gcloud config set pass_credentials_to_gsutil True``.
40	If you do not have ``gcloud`` installed, follow the
41	`Cloud SDK installation instructions. <https://cloud.google.com/sdk/docs/install>`_.
42	
43	
44	<B>TO ENABLE</B>
45	  Set ``use_gcloud_storage=True`` in the ``.boto`` config file under the
46	  ``[GSUtil]`` section:
47	
48	    [GSUtil]
49	    use_gcloud_storage=True
50	
51	  You can also set the flag for individual commands using the top-level ``-o``
52	  flag:
53	
54	    gsutil -o "GSUtil:use_gcloud_storage=True" -m cp -p file gs://bucket/obj
55	
56	<B>AVAILABLE COMMANDS</B>
57	  The gcloud storage CLI only supports a subset of gsutil commands. What follows
58	  is a list of commands supported by the shim with any differences in behavior
59	  noted.
60	
61	  acl
62	  ------------------------
63	
64	  - The ``ch`` subcommand is not supported.
65	
66	  autoclass
67	  ------------------------
68	
69	  - Works as expected.
70	
71	  bucketpolicyonly
72	  ------------------------
73	
74	  - Works as expected.
75	
76	  cat
77	  ------------------------
78	
79	  - Prints object data for a second object even if the first object is invalid.
80	
81	  compose
82	  ------------------------
83	
84	  - Works as expected.
85	
86	  cors
87	  ------------------------
88	
89	  - ``get`` subcommand prints "[]" instead of "gs://[bucket name] has no CORS
90	    configuration".
91	
92	  cp
93	  ------------------------
94	
95	  - Copies a second object even if the first object is invalid.
96	  - Does not support file to file copies.
97	  - Supports copying objects cloud-to-cloud with trailing slashes in the name.
98	  - The all-version flag (``-A``) silently enables sequential execution rather
99	    than raising an error.
100	
101	  defacl
102	  ------------------------
103	
104	  - The ``ch`` subcommand is not supported.
105	
106	  defstorageclass
107	  ------------------------
108	
109	  - Works as expected.
110	
111	  hash
112	  ------------------------
113	
114	  - In gsutil, the ``-m`` and ``-c`` flags that affect which hashes are displayed
115	    are ignored for cloud objects. This behavior is fixed for the shim and gcloud
116	    storage.
117	
118	  iam
119	  ------------------------
120	
121	  - The ``ch`` subcommand is not supported.
122	  - The ``-f`` flag will continue on any error, not just API errors.
123	
124	
125	  kms
126	  ------------------------
127	
128	  - The authorize subcommand returns informational messages in a different
129	    format.
130	  - The encryption subcommand returns informational messages in a different
131	    format.
132	
133	  labels
134	  ------------------------
135	  - ``get`` subcommand prints "[]" instead of "gs://[bucket name] has no labels
136	    configuration."
137	
138	  lifecycle
139	  ------------------------
140	
141	  - Works as expected.
142	
143	  logging
144	  ------------------------
145	
146	  - The get subcommand has different JSON spacing and doesn't print an
147	    informational message if no configuration is found.
148	
149	  ls
150	  ------------------------
151	
152	  - `ls -L` output uses spaces instead of tabs.
153	
154	  mb
155	  ------------------------
156	  - Works as expected.
157	
158	  mv
159	  ------------------------
160	
161	  - See notes on cp.
162	
163	  notification
164	  ------------------------
165	
166	  - The list subcommand prints configuration information as YAML.
167	  - The delete subcommand offers progress tracking and parallelization.
168	
169	  pap
170	  ------------------------
171	
172	  - Works as expected.
173	
174	  rb
175	  ------------------------
176	
177	  - Works as expected.
178	
179	  requesterpays
180	  ------------------------
181	
182	  - Works as expected.
183	
184	  rewrite
185	  ------------------------
186	
187	  - The -k flag does not throw an error if called without a new key. In both the
188	    shim and unshimmed cases, the old key is maintained.
189	
190	  rm
191	  ------------------------
192	
193	  - ``$folder$`` delete markers are not supported.
194	
195	  rpo
196	  ------------------------
197	
198	  - Works as expected.
199	
200	  setmeta
201	  ------------------------
202	
203	  - Does not throw an error if no headers are changed.
204	
205	  stat
206	  ------------------------
207	
208	  - Includes a field "Storage class update time:" which may throw off tabbing.
209	
210	  ubla
211	  ------------------------
212	
213	  - Works as expected.
214	
215	  versioning
216	  ------------------------
217	
218	  - Works as expected.
219	
220	  web
221	  ------------------------
222	
223	  - The get subcommand has different JSON spacing and doesn't print an
224	    informational message if no configuration is found.
225	
226	
227	
228	<B>BOTO CONFIGURATION</B>
229	  Configuration found in the boto file is mapped 1:1 to gcloud environment
230	  variables where appropriate.
231	
232	  Important: The ``gs_oauth2_refresh_token`` and ``gs_service_key_file`` fields
233	  are ignored by the shim and authentication is taken care by ``gcloud``.
234	
235	  [Credentials]
236	  ------------------------
237	
238	  - aws_access_key_id: AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
239	  - aws_secret_access_key: AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
240	  - use_client_certificate: CLOUDSDK_CONTEXT_AWARE_USE_CLIENT_CERTIFICATE
241	
242	  [Boto]
243	  ------------------------
244	
245	  - proxy: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_ADDRESS
246	  - proxy_type: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_TYPE
247	  - proxy_port: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_PORT
248	  - proxy_user: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_USERNAME
249	  - proxy_pass: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_PASSWORD
250	  - proxy_rdns: CLOUDSDK_PROXY_RDNS
251	  - http_socket_timeout: CLOUDSDK_CORE_HTTP_TIMEOUT
252	  - ca_certificates_file: CLOUDSDK_CORE_CUSTOM_CA_CERTS_FILE
253	  - max_retry_delay: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_BASE_RETRY_DELAY
254	  - num_retries: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_MAX_RETRIES
255	
256	  [GSUtil]
257	  ------------------------
258	
259	  - check_hashes: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_CHECK_HASHES
260	  - default_project_id: CLOUDSDK_CORE_PROJECT
261	  - disable_analytics_prompt: CLOUDSDK_CORE_DISABLE_USAGE_REPORTING
262	  - use_magicfile: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_USE_MAGICFILE
263	  - parallel_composite_upload_threshold: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_PARALLEL_COMPOSITE_UPLOAD_THRESHOLD
264	  - resumable_threshold: CLOUDSDK_STORAGE_RESUMABLE_THRESHOLD
265	
266	  [OAuth2]
267	  ------------------------
268	
269	  - client_id: CLOUDSDK_AUTH_CLIENT_ID
270	  - client_secret: CLOUDSDK_AUTH_CLIENT_SECRET
271	  - provider_authorization_uri: CLOUDSDK_AUTH_AUTH_HOST
272	  - provider_token_uri: CLOUDSDK_AUTH_TOKEN_HOST
273	
274	<B>GENERAL COMPATIBILITY NOTES</B>
275	
276	  - Due to its compatibility across all major platforms, multiprocessing is
277	    enabled for all commands by default (equivalent to the -m option always
278	    being included in gsutil).
279	  - A sequence of asterisks greater than 2 (i.e. ``***``) are always treated as
280	    a single asterisk.
281	  - Unlike gsutil, gcloud is not designed to be used in parallel invocations,
282	    and doing so (i.e. running the shim from 2 terminals at once) can lead to
283	    unpredictable behavior.
284	  - Assuming a bucket contains an object ``gs://bucket/nested/foo.txt``,
285	    gsutil's wildcard iterator will match ``foo.txt`` given a URL like
286	    ``gs://bucket/*/nested/*``. The shim will not match ``foo.txt`` given the
287	    same URL.
288	  - This will be updated as new commands are supported by both gcloud storage
289	    and the shim.
290	  - If Unicode is having issues, try setting the environment variable
291	    ``PYTHONUTF8`` to ``1``. Specifically, this may help on the Windows
292	    command-line (CMD).
293	
294	""")
295

61

64	  providing the gsutil -D output noted above. We cannot support versions

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/addlhelp/versions.py:24
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html

24	_DETAILED_HELP_TEXT = ("""
25	<B>OVERVIEW</B>
26	  Versioning-enabled buckets maintain noncurrent versions of objects, providing
27	  a way to un-delete data that you accidentally deleted, or to retrieve older
28	  versions of your data. Noncurrent objects are ignored by gsutil commands
29	  unless you indicate it should do otherwise by setting a relevant command flag
30	  or by including a specific generation number in your command. For example,
31	  wildcards like ``*`` and ``**`` do not, by themselves, act on noncurrent
32	  object versions.
33	  
34	  When using gsutil cp, you cannot specify a version-specific URL as the
35	  destination, because writes to Cloud Storage always create a new version.
36	  Trying to specify a version-specific URL as the destination of ``gsutil cp``
37	  results in an error. When you specify a noncurrent object as a source in a
38	  copy command, you always create a new object version and retain the original
39	  (even when using the command to restore a live version). You can use the 
40	  ``gsutil mv`` command to simultaneously restore an object version and remove
41	  the noncurrent copy that was used as the source.
42	
43	  You can turn versioning on or off for a bucket at any time. Turning
44	  versioning off leaves existing object versions in place and simply causes
45	  the bucket to delete the existing live version of the object whenever a new
46	  version is uploaded.
47	
48	  Regardless of whether you have enabled versioning on a bucket, every object
49	  has two associated positive integer fields:
50	
51	  - the generation, which is updated when a new object replaces an existing
52	    object with the same name. Note that there is no guarantee that generation
53	    numbers increase for successive versions, only that each new version has a
54	    unique generation number.
55	  - the metageneration, which identifies the metadata generation. It starts
56	    at 1; is updated every time the metadata (e.g., ACL or Content-Type) for a
57	    given content generation is updated; and gets reset when the generation
58	    number changes.
59	
60	  Of these two integers, only the generation is used when working with versioned
61	  data. Both generation and metageneration can be used with concurrency control.
62	  
63	  To learn more about versioning and concurrency, see the following documentation:
64	  
65	  - `Overview of Object Versioning
66	    <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/object-versioning>`_
67	  - `Guide for using Object Versioning
68	    <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/using-object-versioning>`_
69	  - The `reference page for the gsutil versioning command
70	    <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/gsutil/commands/versioning>`_
71	  - `Request preconditions
72	    <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/request-preconditions>`_
73	""")

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/acl.py:74
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html

74	_SET_DESCRIPTION = """
75	<B>SET</B>
76	  The ``acl set`` command allows you to set an Access Control List on one or
77	  more buckets and objects. As part of the command, you must specify either a
78	  predefined ACL or the path to a file that contains ACL text. The simplest way
79	  to use the ``acl set`` command is to specify one of the predefined ACLs,
80	  e.g.,:
81	
82	    gsutil acl set private gs://example-bucket/example-object
83	
84	  If you want to make an object or bucket publicly readable or writable, it is
85	  recommended to use ``acl ch``, to avoid accidentally removing OWNER
86	  permissions. See the ``acl ch`` section for details.
87	
88	  See `Predefined ACLs
89	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/access-control/lists#predefined-acl>`_
90	  for a list of predefined ACLs.
91	
92	  If you want to define more fine-grained control over your data, you can
93	  retrieve an ACL using the ``acl get`` command, save the output to a file, edit
94	  the file, and then use the ``acl set`` command to set that ACL on the buckets
95	  and/or objects. For example:
96	
97	    gsutil acl get gs://bucket/file.txt > acl.txt
98	
99	  Make changes to acl.txt such as adding an additional grant, then:
100	
101	    gsutil acl set acl.txt gs://cats/file.txt
102	
103	  Note that you can set an ACL on multiple buckets or objects at once. For
104	  example, to set ACLs on all .jpg files found in a bucket:
105	
106	    gsutil acl set acl.txt gs://bucket/**.jpg
107	
108	  If you have a large number of ACLs to update you might want to use the
109	  gsutil -m option, to perform a parallel (multi-threaded/multi-processing)
110	  update:
111	
112	    gsutil -m acl set acl.txt gs://bucket/**.jpg
113	
114	  Note that multi-threading/multi-processing is only done when the named URLs
115	  refer to objects, which happens either if you name specific objects or
116	  if you enumerate objects by using an object wildcard or specifying
117	  the acl -r flag.
118	
119	
120	<B>SET OPTIONS</B>
121	  The "set" sub-command has the following options
122	
123	  -R, -r      Performs "acl set" request recursively, to all objects under
124	              the specified URL.
125	
126	  -a          Performs "acl set" request on all object versions.
127	
128	  -f          Normally gsutil stops at the first error. The -f option causes
129	              it to continue when it encounters errors. If some of the ACLs
130	              couldn't be set, gsutil's exit status will be non-zero even if
131	              this flag is set. This option is implicitly set when running
132	              "gsutil -m acl...".
133	"""
134	
135	_CH_DESCRIPTION = """

--------------------------------------------------
>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/acl.py:135
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
134	
135	_CH_DESCRIPTION = """
136	<B>CH</B>
137	  The "acl ch" (or "acl change") command updates access control lists, similar
138	  in spirit to the Linux chmod command. You can specify multiple access grant
139	  additions and deletions in a single command run; all changes will be made
140	  atomically to each object in turn. For example, if the command requests
141	  deleting one grant and adding a different grant, the ACLs being updated will
142	  never be left in an intermediate state where one grant has been deleted but
143	  the second grant not yet added. Each change specifies a user or group grant
144	  to add or delete, and for grant additions, one of R, W, O (for the
145	  permission to be granted). A more formal description is provided in a later
146	  section; below we provide examples.
147	
148	<B>CH EXAMPLES</B>
149	  Examples for "ch" sub-command:
150	
151	  Grant anyone on the internet READ access to the object example-object:
152	
153	    gsutil acl ch -u allUsers:R gs://example-bucket/example-object
154	
155	  NOTE: By default, publicly readable objects are served with a Cache-Control
156	  header allowing such objects to be cached for 3600 seconds. If you need to
157	  ensure that updates become visible immediately, you should set a
158	  Cache-Control header of "Cache-Control:private, max-age=0, no-transform" on
159	  such objects. For help doing this, see "gsutil help setmeta".
160	
161	  Grant the user john.doe@example.com READ access to all objects
162	  in example-bucket that begin with folder/:
163	
164	    gsutil acl ch -r -u john.doe@example.com:R gs://example-bucket/folder/
165	
166	  Grant the group admins@example.com OWNER access to all jpg files in
167	  example-bucket:
168	
169	    gsutil acl ch -g admins@example.com:O gs://example-bucket/**.jpg
170	
171	  Grant the owners of project example-project WRITE access to the bucket
172	  example-bucket:
173	
174	    gsutil acl ch -p owners-example-project:W gs://example-bucket
175	
176	  NOTE: You can replace 'owners' with 'viewers' or 'editors' to grant access
177	  to a project's viewers/editors respectively.
178	
179	  Remove access to the bucket example-bucket for the viewers of project number
180	  12345:
181	
182	    gsutil acl ch -d viewers-12345 gs://example-bucket
183	
184	  NOTE: You cannot remove the project owners group from ACLs of gs:// buckets in
185	  the given project. Attempts to do so will appear to succeed, but the service
186	  will add the project owners group into the new set of ACLs before applying it.
187	
188	  Note that removing a project requires you to reference the project by
189	  its number (which you can see with the acl get command) as opposed to its
190	  project ID string.
191	
192	  Grant the service account foo@developer.gserviceaccount.com WRITE access to
193	  the bucket example-bucket:
194	
195	    gsutil acl ch -u foo@developer.gserviceaccount.com:W gs://example-bucket
196	
197	  Grant all users from the `G Suite
198	  <https://www.google.com/work/apps/business/>`_ domain my-domain.org READ
199	  access to the bucket gcs.my-domain.org:
200	
201	    gsutil acl ch -g my-domain.org:R gs://gcs.my-domain.org
202	
203	  Remove any current access by john.doe@example.com from the bucket
204	  example-bucket:
205	
206	    gsutil acl ch -d john.doe@example.com gs://example-bucket
207	
208	  If you have a large number of objects to update, enabling multi-threading
209	  with the gsutil -m flag can significantly improve performance. The
210	  following command adds OWNER for admin@example.org using
211	  multi-threading:
212	
213	    gsutil -m acl ch -r -u admin@example.org:O gs://example-bucket
214	
215	  Grant READ access to everyone from my-domain.org and to all authenticated
216	  users, and grant OWNER to admin@mydomain.org, for the buckets
217	  my-bucket and my-other-bucket, with multi-threading enabled:
218	
219	    gsutil -m acl ch -r -g my-domain.org:R -g AllAuth:R \\
220	      -u admin@mydomain.org:O gs://my-bucket/ gs://my-other-bucket
221	
222	<B>CH ROLES</B>
223	  You may specify the following roles with either their shorthand or
224	  their full name:
225	
226	    R: READ
227	    W: WRITE
228	    O: OWNER
229	
230	  For more information on these roles and the access they grant, see the
231	  permissions section of the `Access Control Lists page
232	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/access-control/lists#permissions>`_.
233	
234	<B>CH ENTITIES</B>
235	  There are four different entity types: Users, Groups, All Authenticated Users,
236	  and All Users.
237	
238	  Users are added with -u and a plain ID or email address, as in
239	  "-u john-doe@gmail.com:r". Note: Service Accounts are considered to be users.
240	
241	  Groups are like users, but specified with the -g flag, as in
242	  "-g power-users@example.com:O". Groups may also be specified as a full
243	  domain, as in "-g my-company.com:r".
244	
245	  allAuthenticatedUsers and allUsers are specified directly, as
246	  in "-g allUsers:R" or "-g allAuthenticatedUsers:O". These are case
247	  insensitive, and may be shortened to "all" and "allauth", respectively.
248	
249	  Removing roles is specified with the -d flag and an ID, email
250	  address, domain, or one of allUsers or allAuthenticatedUsers.
251	
252	  Many entities' roles can be specified on the same command line, allowing
253	  bundled changes to be executed in a single run. This will reduce the number of
254	  requests made to the server.
255	
256	<B>CH OPTIONS</B>
257	  The "ch" sub-command has the following options
258	
259	  -d          Remove all roles associated with the matching entity.
260	
261	  -f          Normally gsutil stops at the first error. The -f option causes
262	              it to continue when it encounters errors. With this option the
263	              gsutil exit status will be 0 even if some ACLs couldn't be
264	              changed.
265	
266	  -g          Add or modify a group entity's role.
267	
268	  -p          Add or modify a project viewers/editors/owners role.
269	
270	  -R, -r      Performs acl ch request recursively, to all objects under the
271	              specified URL.
272	
273	  -u          Add or modify a user entity's role.
274	"""
275

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/config.py:265

265	CONFIG_INPUTLESS_GSUTIL_SECTION_CONTENT = """
266	[GSUtil]
267	
268	# 'resumable_threshold' specifies the smallest file size [bytes] for which
269	# resumable Google Cloud Storage uploads are attempted. The default is 8388608
270	# (8 MiB).
271	#resumable_threshold = %(resumable_threshold)d
272	
273	# 'rsync_buffer_lines' specifies the number of lines of bucket or directory
274	# listings saved in each temp file during sorting. (The complete set is
275	# split across temp files and separately sorted/merged, to avoid needing to
276	# fit everything in memory at once.) If you are trying to synchronize very
277	# large directories/buckets (e.g., containing millions or more objects),
278	# having too small a value here can cause gsutil to run out of open file
279	# handles. If that happens, you can try to increase the number of open file
280	# handles your system allows (e.g., see 'man ulimit' on Linux; see also
281	# http://docs.python.org/2/library/resource.html). If you can't do that (or
282	# if you're already at the upper limit), increasing rsync_buffer_lines will
283	# cause gsutil to use fewer file handles, but at the cost of more memory. With
284	# rsync_buffer_lines set to 32000 and assuming a typical URL is 100 bytes
285	# long, gsutil will require approximately 10 MiB of memory while building
286	# the synchronization state, and will require approximately 60 open file
287	# descriptors to build the synchronization state over all 1M source and 1M
288	# destination URLs. Memory and file descriptors are only consumed while
289	# building the state; once the state is built, it resides in two temp files that
290	# are read and processed incrementally during the actual copy/delete
291	# operations.
292	#rsync_buffer_lines = 32000
293	
294	# 'state_dir' specifies the base location where files that
295	# need a static location are stored, such as pointers to credentials,
296	# resumable transfer tracker files, and the last software update check.
297	# By default these files are stored in ~/.gsutil
298	#state_dir = <file_path>
299	# gsutil periodically checks whether a new version of the gsutil software is
300	# available. 'software_update_check_period' specifies the number of days
301	# between such checks. The default is 30. Setting the value to 0 disables
302	# periodic software update checks.
303	#software_update_check_period = 30
304	
305	# 'tab_completion_timeout' controls the timeout (in seconds) for tab
306	# completions that involve remote requests (such as bucket or object names).
307	# If tab completion does not succeed within this timeout, no tab completion
308	# suggestions will be returned.
309	# A value of 0 will disable completions that involve remote requests.
310	#tab_completion_timeout = 5
311	
312	# 'parallel_process_count' and 'parallel_thread_count' specify the number
313	# of OS processes and Python threads, respectively, to use when executing
314	# operations in parallel. The default settings should work well as configured,
315	# however, to enhance performance for transfers involving large numbers of
316	# files, you may experiment with hand tuning these values to optimize
317	# performance for your particular system configuration.
318	#parallel_process_count = %(parallel_process_count)d
319	#parallel_thread_count = %(parallel_thread_count)d
320	
321	# 'parallel_composite_upload_threshold' specifies the maximum size of a file to
322	# upload in a single stream. Files larger than this threshold will be
323	# partitioned into component parts and uploaded in parallel and then composed
324	# into a single object.
325	# The number of components will be the smaller of
326	# ceil(file_size / parallel_composite_upload_component_size) and
327	# MAX_COMPOSE_ARITY. The current value of MAX_COMPOSE_ARITY is
328	# %(max_compose_arity)d.
329	# If 'parallel_composite_upload_threshold' is set to 0, then automatic parallel
330	# uploads will never occur.
331	# Setting an extremely low threshold is unadvisable. The vast majority of
332	# environments will see degraded performance for thresholds below 80M, and it
333	# is almost never advantageous to have a threshold below 20M.
334	# 'parallel_composite_upload_component_size' specifies the ideal size of a
335	# component in bytes, which will act as an upper bound to the size of the
336	# components if ceil(file_size / parallel_composite_upload_component_size) is
337	# less than MAX_COMPOSE_ARITY.
338	# Values can be provided either in bytes or as human-readable values
339	# (e.g., "150M" to represent 150 mebibytes)
340	#
341	# Note: At present parallel composite uploads are disabled by default, because
342	# using composite objects requires a compiled crcmod (see "gsutil help crcmod"),
343	# and for operating systems that don't already have this package installed this
344	# makes gsutil harder to use. Google is actively working with a number of the
345	# Linux distributions to get crcmod included with the stock distribution. Once
346	# that is done we will re-enable parallel composite uploads by default in
347	# gsutil.
348	#
349	# Note: Parallel composite uploads should not be used with NEARLINE, COLDLINE,
350	# or ARCHIVE storage class buckets, as doing this incurs an early deletion
351	# charge for each component object.
352	#
353	# Note: Parallel composite uploads are not enabled with Cloud KMS encrypted
354	# objects as a source or destination, as composition with KMS objects is not yet
355	# supported.
356	
357	#parallel_composite_upload_threshold = %(parallel_composite_upload_threshold)s
358	#parallel_composite_upload_component_size = %(parallel_composite_upload_component_size)s
359	
360	#
361	# 'parallel_composite_upload_bypass_kms_check' removes the object/bucket KMS checks
362	# used to guard composition of KMS objects.
363	#disable_parallel_composite_upload_kms_check = False
364	
365	# 'sliced_object_download_threshold' and
366	# 'sliced_object_download_component_size' have analogous functionality to
367	# their respective parallel_composite_upload config values.
368	# 'sliced_object_download_max_components' specifies the maximum number of
369	# slices to be used when performing a sliced object download.
370	#sliced_object_download_threshold = %(sliced_object_download_threshold)s
371	#sliced_object_download_component_size = %(sliced_object_download_component_size)s
372	#sliced_object_download_max_components = %(sliced_object_download_max_components)s
373	
374	# Compressed transport encoded uploads buffer chunks of compressed data. When
375	# running a composite upload and/or many uploads in parallel, compression may
376	# consume more memory than available. This setting restricts the number of
377	# compressed transport encoded uploads running in parallel such that they
378	# don't consume more memory than set here. This is 2GiB by default.
379	# Values can be provided either in bytes or as human-readable values
380	# (e.g., "2G" to represent 2 gibibytes)
381	#max_upload_compression_buffer_size = %(max_upload_compression_buffer_size)s
382	
383	# GZIP compression level, if using compression. Reducing this can have
384	# a dramatic impact on compression speed with minor size increases.
385	# This is a value from 0-9, with 9 being max compression.
386	# A good level to try is 6, which is the default used by the gzip tool.
387	#gzip_compression_level = %(gzip_compression_level)s
388	
389	# 'task_estimation_threshold' controls how many files or objects gsutil
390	# processes before it attempts to estimate the total work that will be
391	# performed by the command. Estimation makes extra directory listing or API
392	# list calls and is performed only if multiple processes and/or threads are
393	# used. Estimation can slightly increase cost due to extra
394	# listing calls; to disable it entirely, set this value to 0.
395	#task_estimation_threshold=%(task_estimation_threshold)s
396	
397	# 'use_magicfile' specifies if the 'file --mime <filename>' command should be
398	# used to guess content types instead of the default filename extension-based
399	# mechanism. Available on UNIX and macOS (and possibly on Windows, if you're
400	# running Cygwin or some other package that provides implementations of
401	# UNIX-like commands). When available and enabled use_magicfile should be more
402	# robust because it analyzes file contents in addition to extensions.
403	#use_magicfile = False
404	
405	# Service account emails for testing the hmac command. If these fields are not
406	# populated with distinct service accounts the tests for the hmac command will
407	# not be run.  Primarily useful for tool developers.
408	#test_hmac_service_account =
409	#test_hmac_alt_service_account =

411	
412	# Service account emails for testing impersonation credentials. If this field is
413	# not populated with a service account the tests for service account
414	# impersonation will not run.  Primarily useful for tool developers.
415	#test_impersonate_service_account =
416	
417	# 'content_language' specifies the ISO 639-1 language code of the content, to be
418	# passed in the Content-Language header. By default no Content-Language is sent.
419	# See the ISO 639-1 column of
420	# http://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/php/code_list.php for a list of
421	# language codes.
422	content_language = en
423	
424	# 'check_hashes' specifies how strictly to require integrity checking for
425	# downloaded data. Legal values are:
426	#   '%(hash_fast_else_fail)s' - (default) Only integrity check if the digest
427	#       will run efficiently (using compiled code), else fail the download.
428	#   '%(hash_fast_else_skip)s' - Only integrity check if the server supplies a
429	#       hash and the local digest computation will run quickly, else skip the
430	#       check.
431	#   '%(hash_always)s' - Always check download integrity regardless of possible
432	#       performance costs.
433	#   '%(hash_never)s' - Don't perform download integrity checks. This setting is
434	#       not recommended except for special cases such as measuring download
435	#       performance excluding time for integrity checking.
436	# This option exists to assist users who wish to download a GCS composite object
437	# and are unable to install crcmod with the C-extension. CRC32c is the only
438	# available integrity check for composite objects, and without the C-extension,
439	# download performance can be significantly degraded by the digest computation.
440	# This option is ignored for daisy-chain copies, which don't compute hashes but
441	# instead (inexpensively) compare the cloud source and destination hashes.
442	#check_hashes = if_fast_else_fail
443	
444	# 'encryption_key' specifies a single customer-supplied encryption key that
445	# will be used for all data written to Google Cloud Storage. See
446	# "gsutil help encryption" for more information
447	# Encryption key: RFC 4648 section 4 base64-encoded AES256 string
448	# Warning: If decrypt_key is specified without an encrypt_key, objects will be
449	# decrypted when copied in the cloud.
450	#encryption_key=
451	
452	# Each 'decryption_key' entry specifies a customer-supplied decryption key that
453	# will be used to access and Google Cloud Storage objects encrypted with
454	# the corresponding key.
455	# Decryption keys: Up to 100 RFC 4648 section 4 base64-encoded AES256 strings
456	# in ascending numerical order, starting with 1.
457	#decryption_key1=
458	#decryption_key2=
459	#decryption_key3=
460	
461	# The ability to specify an alternative JSON API version is primarily for cloud
462	# storage service developers.
463	#json_api_version = v1
464	
465	# Specifies the API to use when interacting with cloud storage providers. If the
466	# gsutil command supports this API for the provider, it will be used instead of
467	# the default API. Commands typically default to XML for S3 and JSON for GCS.
468	# Note that if any encryption configuration options are set (see above), the
469	# JSON API will be used for interacting with Google Cloud Storage buckets even
470	# if XML is preferred, as gsutil does not currently support this functionality
471	# when using the XML API.
472	#prefer_api = json
473	#prefer_api = xml
474	
475	# Disables the prompt asking for opt-in to data collection for analytics.
476	#disable_analytics_prompt = True
477	
478	# The "test" command runs tests against regional buckets (unless you supply the
479	# `-b` option). By default, the region used is us-central1, but you can change
480	# the default region using this option.
481	#test_cmd_regional_bucket_location = us-central1
482	
483	# Tests for the "notification watchbucket" command require a notification URL.
484	# If this option is not supplied, those tests will be skipped.
485	#test_notification_url = https://yourdomain.url/notification-endpoint
486	
487	# Used in conjunction with --stet flag on cp command for end-to-end encryption.
488	# STET binary path. If not specified, gsutil checks PATH for "stet".
489	#stet_binary_path = <Path to binary "/usr/local/bin/stet">
490	
491	# STET config path. If not specified, the STET binary will run with its default
492	# settings.
493	#stet_config_path = ~/.config/my_config.yaml
494	
495	# Adds an API call before parallel operations that triggers a reauth challenge.
496	#trigger_reauth_challenge_for_parallel_operations = False
497

523	CONFIG_OAUTH2_CONFIG_CONTENT = """
524	[OAuth2]
525	# This section specifies options used with OAuth2 authentication.
526	
527	# 'token_cache' specifies how the OAuth2 client should cache access tokens.
528	# Valid values are:
529	#  'in_memory': an in-memory cache is used. This is only useful if the boto
530	#      client instance (and with it the OAuth2 plugin instance) persists
531	#      across multiple requests.
532	#  'file_system' : access tokens will be cached in the file system, in files
533	#      whose names include a key derived from the refresh token the access token
534	#      based on.
535	# The default is 'file_system'.
536	#token_cache = file_system
537	#token_cache = in_memory
538	
539	# 'token_cache_path_pattern' specifies a path pattern for token cache files.
540	# This option is only relevant if token_cache = file_system.
541	# The value of this option should be a path, with place-holders '%(key)s' (which
542	# will be replaced with a key derived from the refresh token the cached access
543	# token was based on), and (optionally), %(uid)s (which will be replaced with
544	# the UID of the current user, if available via os.getuid()).
545	# Note that the config parser itself interpolates '%' placeholders, and hence
546	# the above placeholders need to be escaped as '%%(key)s'.
547	# The default value of this option is
548	#  token_cache_path_pattern = <tmpdir>/oauth2client-tokencache.%%(uid)s.%%(key)s
549	# where <tmpdir> is the system-dependent default temp directory.
550	
551	# The following options specify the label and endpoint URIs for the OAUth2
552	# authorization provider being used. Primarily useful for tool developers.
553	#provider_label = Google
554	#provider_authorization_uri = https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth
555	#provider_token_uri = https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token
556	
557	# 'oauth2_refresh_retries' controls the number of retry attempts made when
558	# rate limiting errors occur for OAuth2 requests to retrieve an access token.
559	# The default value is 6.
560	#oauth2_refresh_retries = <integer value>
561	
562	# The following options specify the OAuth2 client identity and secret that is
563	# used when requesting and using OAuth2 tokens. If not specified, a default
564	# OAuth2 client for the gsutil tool is used; for uses of the boto library (with
565	# OAuth2 authentication plugin) in other client software, it is recommended to
566	# use a tool/client-specific OAuth2 client. For more information on OAuth2, see
567	# http://code.google.com/apis/accounts/docs/OAuth2.html
568	"""

63	_DESCRIPTION = ("""
64	  Gets or sets the Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) configuration on one or
65	  more buckets. This command is supported for buckets only, not objects. An
66	  example CORS JSON file looks like the following:
67	
68	    [
69	      {
70	        "origin": ["http://origin1.example.com"],
71	        "responseHeader": ["Content-Type"],
72	        "method": ["GET"],
73	        "maxAgeSeconds": 3600
74	      }
75	    ]
76	
77	  The above CORS configuration explicitly allows cross-origin GET requests from
78	  http://origin1.example.com and may include the Content-Type response header.
79	  The preflight request may be cached for 1 hour.
80	
81	  Note that requests to the authenticated browser download endpoint ``storage.cloud.google.com``
82	  do not allow CORS requests. For more information about supported endpoints for CORS, see
83	  `Cloud Storage CORS support <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/cross-origin#server-side-support>`_.
84	
85	  The following (empty) CORS JSON file removes any CORS configuration for a
86	  bucket:
87	
88	    []
89	
90	  The cors command has two sub-commands:
91	""" + '\n'.join([_GET_DESCRIPTION, _SET_DESCRIPTION]) + """
92	For more info about CORS generally, see https://www.w3.org/TR/cors/.

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium

84	_DESCRIPTION_TEXT = """
85	<B>DESCRIPTION</B>
86	  The ``gsutil cp`` command allows you to copy data between your local file
87	  system and the cloud, within the cloud, and between
88	  cloud storage providers. For example, to upload all text files from the
89	  local directory to a bucket, you can run:
90	
91	    gsutil cp *.txt gs://my-bucket
92	
93	  You can also download data from a bucket. The following command downloads
94	  all text files from the top-level of a bucket to your current directory:
95	
96	    gsutil cp gs://my-bucket/*.txt .
97	
98	  You can use the ``-n`` option to prevent overwriting the content of
99	  existing files. The following example downloads text files from a bucket
100	  without clobbering the data in your directory:
101	
102	    gsutil cp -n gs://my-bucket/*.txt .
103	
104	  Use the ``-r`` option to copy an entire directory tree.
105	  For example, to upload the directory tree ``dir``:
106	
107	    gsutil cp -r dir gs://my-bucket
108	
109	  If you have a large number of files to transfer, you can perform a parallel
110	  multi-threaded/multi-processing copy using the
111	  top-level gsutil ``-m`` option (see "gsutil help options"):
112	
113	    gsutil -m cp -r dir gs://my-bucket
114	
115	  You can use the ``-I`` option with ``stdin`` to specify a list of URLs to
116	  copy, one per line. This allows you to use gsutil
117	  in a pipeline to upload or download objects as generated by a program:
118	
119	    cat filelist | gsutil -m cp -I gs://my-bucket
120	
121	  or:
122	
123	    cat filelist | gsutil -m cp -I ./download_dir
124	
125	  where the output of ``cat filelist`` is a list of files, cloud URLs, and
126	  wildcards of files and cloud URLs.
127	
128	  NOTE: Shells like ``bash`` and ``zsh`` sometimes attempt to expand
129	  wildcards in ways that can be surprising. You may also encounter issues when
130	  attempting to copy files whose names contain wildcard characters. For more
131	  details about these issues, see `Wildcard behavior considerations
132	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/wildcards#surprising-behavior>`_.
133	"""
134	
135	_NAME_CONSTRUCTION_TEXT = """

--------------------------------------------------
>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/cp.py:135
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
134	
135	_NAME_CONSTRUCTION_TEXT = """
136	<B>HOW NAMES ARE CONSTRUCTED</B>
137	  The ``gsutil cp`` command attempts to name objects in ways that are consistent with the
138	  Linux ``cp`` command. This means that names are constructed depending
139	  on whether you're performing a recursive directory copy or copying
140	  individually-named objects, or whether you're copying to an existing or
141	  non-existent directory.
142	
143	  When you perform recursive directory copies, object names are constructed to
144	  mirror the source directory structure starting at the point of recursive
145	  processing. For example, if ``dir1/dir2`` contains the file ``a/b/c``, then the
146	  following command creates the object ``gs://my-bucket/dir2/a/b/c``:
147	
148	    gsutil cp -r dir1/dir2 gs://my-bucket
149	
150	  In contrast, copying individually-named files results in objects named by
151	  the final path component of the source files. For example, assuming again that
152	  ``dir1/dir2`` contains ``a/b/c``, the following command creates the object
153	  ``gs://my-bucket/c``:
154	
155	    gsutil cp dir1/dir2/** gs://my-bucket
156	
157	  Note that in the above example, the '**' wildcard matches all names
158	  anywhere under ``dir``. The wildcard '*' matches names just one level deep. For
159	  more details, see `URI wildcards
160	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/wildcards#surprising-behavior>`_.
161	
162	  The same rules apply for uploads and downloads: recursive copies of buckets and
163	  bucket subdirectories produce a mirrored filename structure, while copying
164	  individually or wildcard-named objects produce flatly-named files.
165	
166	  In addition, the resulting names depend on whether the destination subdirectory
167	  exists. For example, if ``gs://my-bucket/subdir`` exists as a subdirectory,
168	  the following command creates the object ``gs://my-bucket/subdir/dir2/a/b/c``:
169	
170	    gsutil cp -r dir1/dir2 gs://my-bucket/subdir
171	
172	  In contrast, if ``gs://my-bucket/subdir`` does not exist, this same ``gsutil cp``
173	  command creates the object ``gs://my-bucket/subdir/a/b/c``.
174	
175	  NOTE: The
176	  `Google Cloud Platform Console <https://console.cloud.google.com>`_
177	  creates folders by creating "placeholder" objects that end
178	  with a "/" character. gsutil skips these objects when downloading from the
179	  cloud to the local file system, because creating a file that
180	  ends with a "/" is not allowed on Linux and macOS. We
181	  recommend that you only create objects that end with "/" if you don't
182	  intend to download such objects using gsutil.
183	"""
184

272	_RETRY_HANDLING_TEXT = """
273	<B>RETRY HANDLING</B>
274	  The ``cp`` command retries when failures occur, but if enough failures happen
275	  during a particular copy or delete operation, or if a failure isn't retryable,
276	  the ``cp`` command skips that object and moves on. If any failures were not
277	  successfully retried by the end of the copy run, the ``cp`` command reports the
278	  number of failures and exits with a non-zero status.
279	
280	  For details about gsutil's overall retry handling, see `Retry strategy
281	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/retry-strategy#tools>`_.
282	"""

284	_RESUMABLE_TRANSFERS_TEXT = """
285	<B>RESUMABLE TRANSFERS</B>
286	  gsutil automatically resumes interrupted downloads and interrupted `resumable
287	  uploads <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/resumable-uploads#gsutil>`_,
288	  except when performing streaming transfers. In the case of an interrupted
289	  download, a partially downloaded temporary file is visible in the destination
290	  directory with the suffix ``_.gstmp`` in its name. Upon completion, the
291	  original file is deleted and replaced with the downloaded contents.
292	
293	  Resumable transfers store state information in files under
294	  ~/.gsutil, named by the destination object or file.
295	
296	  See "gsutil help prod" for details on using resumable transfers
297	  in production.
298	"""

300	_STREAMING_TRANSFERS_TEXT = """
301	<B>STREAMING TRANSFERS</B>
302	  Use '-' in place of src_url or dst_url to perform a `streaming transfer
303	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/streaming>`_.
304	
305	  Streaming uploads using the `JSON API
306	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/request-endpoints#gsutil>`_ are buffered
307	  in memory part-way back into the file and can thus sometimes resume in the event
308	  of network or service problems.
309	
310	  gsutil does not support resuming streaming uploads using the XML API or
311	  resuming streaming downloads for either JSON or XML. If you have a large amount
312	  of data to transfer in these cases, we recommend that you write the data to a
313	  local file and copy that file rather than streaming it.
314	"""

373	
374	_OPTIONS_TEXT = """
375	<B>OPTIONS</B>
376	  -a predef_acl  Applies the specific predefined ACL to uploaded objects. See
377	                 "gsutil help acls" for further details.
378	
379	  -A             Copy all source versions from a source bucket or folder.
380	                 If not set, only the live version of each source object is
381	                 copied.
382	
383	                 NOTE: This option is only useful when the destination
384	                 bucket has Object Versioning enabled. Additionally, the generation
385	                 numbers of copied versions do not necessarily match the order of the
386	                 original generation numbers.
387	
388	  -c             If an error occurs, continue attempting to copy the remaining
389	                 files. If any copies are unsuccessful, gsutil's exit status
390	                 is non-zero, even if this flag is set. This option is
391	                 implicitly set when running ``gsutil -m cp...``.
392	
393	                 NOTE: ``-c`` only applies to the actual copying operation. If an
394	                 error, such as ``invalid Unicode file name``, occurs while iterating
395	                 over the files in the local directory, gsutil prints an error
396	                 message and aborts.
397	
398	  -D             Copy in "daisy chain" mode, which means copying between two buckets
399	                 by first downloading to the machine where gsutil is run, then
400	                 uploading to the destination bucket. The default mode is a
401	                 "copy in the cloud," where data is copied between two buckets without
402	                 uploading or downloading.
403	
404	                 During a "copy in the cloud," a source composite object remains composite
405	                 at its destination. However, you can use "daisy chain" mode to change a
406	                 composite object into a non-composite object. For example:
407	
408	                     gsutil cp -D gs://bucket/obj gs://bucket/obj_tmp
409	                     gsutil mv gs://bucket/obj_tmp gs://bucket/obj
410	
411	                 NOTE: "Daisy chain" mode is automatically used when copying
412	                 between providers: for example, when copying data from Cloud Storage
413	                 to another provider.
414	
415	  -e             Exclude symlinks. When specified, symbolic links are not copied.
416	
417	  -I             Use ``stdin`` to specify a list of files or objects to copy. You can use
418	                 gsutil in a pipeline to upload or download objects as generated by a program.
419	                 For example:
420	
421	                   cat filelist | gsutil -m cp -I gs://my-bucket
422	
423	                 where the output of ``cat filelist`` is a one-per-line list of
424	                 files, cloud URLs, and wildcards of files and cloud URLs.
425	
426	  -j <ext,...>   Applies gzip transport encoding to any file upload whose
427	                 extension matches the ``-j`` extension list. This is useful when
428	                 uploading files with compressible content such as .js, .css,
429	                 or .html files. This also saves network bandwidth while
430	                 leaving the data uncompressed in Cloud Storage.
431	
432	                 When you specify the ``-j`` option, files being uploaded are
433	                 compressed in-memory and on-the-wire only. Both the local
434	                 files and Cloud Storage objects remain uncompressed. The
435	                 uploaded objects retain the ``Content-Type`` and name of the
436	                 original files.
437	
438	                 Note that if you want to use the ``-m`` `top-level option
439	                 <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/gsutil/addlhelp/GlobalCommandLineOptions>`_
440	                 to parallelize copies along with the ``-j/-J`` options, your
441	                 performance may be bottlenecked by the
442	                 "max_upload_compression_buffer_size" boto config option,
443	                 which is set to 2 GiB by default. You can change this
444	                 compression buffer size to a higher limit. For example:
445	
446	                   gsutil -o "GSUtil:max_upload_compression_buffer_size=8G" \\
447	                     -m cp -j html,txt -r /local/source/dir gs://bucket/path
448	
449	  -J             Applies gzip transport encoding to file uploads. This option
450	                 works like the ``-j`` option described above, but it applies to
451	                 all uploaded files, regardless of extension.
452	
453	                 CAUTION: If some of the source files don't compress well, such
454	                 as binary data, using this option may result in longer uploads.
455	
456	  -L <file>      Outputs a manifest log file with detailed information about
457	                 each item that was copied. This manifest contains the following
458	                 information for each item:
459	
460	                 - Source path.
461	                 - Destination path.
462	                 - Source size.
463	                 - Bytes transferred.
464	                 - MD5 hash.
465	                 - Transfer start time and date in UTC and ISO 8601 format.
466	                 - Transfer completion time and date in UTC and ISO 8601 format.
467	                 - Upload id, if a resumable upload was performed.
468	                 - Final result of the attempted transfer, either success or failure.
469	                 - Failure details, if any.
470	
471	                 If the log file already exists, gsutil uses the file as an
472	                 input to the copy process, and appends log items to
473	                 the existing file. Objects that are marked in the
474	                 existing log file as having been successfully copied or
475	                 skipped are ignored. Objects without entries are
476	                 copied and ones previously marked as unsuccessful are
477	                 retried. This option can be used in conjunction with the ``-c`` option to
478	                 build a script that copies a large number of objects reliably,
479	                 using a bash script like the following:
480	
481	                   until gsutil cp -c -L cp.log -r ./dir gs://bucket; do
482	                     sleep 1
483	                   done
484	
485	                 The -c option enables copying to continue after failures
486	                 occur, and the -L option allows gsutil to pick up where it
487	                 left off without duplicating work. The loop continues
488	                 running as long as gsutil exits with a non-zero status. A non-zero
489	                 status indicates there was at least one failure during the copy
490	                 operation.
491	
492	                 NOTE: If you are synchronizing the contents of a
493	                 directory and a bucket, or the contents of two buckets, see
494	                 "gsutil help rsync".
495	
496	  -n             No-clobber. When specified, existing files or objects at the
497	                 destination are not replaced. Any items that are skipped
498	                 by this option are reported as skipped. gsutil
499	                 performs an additional GET request to check if an item
500	                 exists before attempting to upload the data. This saves gsutil
501	                 from retransmitting data, but the additional HTTP requests may make
502	                 small object transfers slower and more expensive.
503	
504	  -p             Preserves ACLs when copying in the cloud. Note
505	                 that this option has performance and cost implications only when
506	                 using the XML API, as the XML API requires separate HTTP calls for
507	                 interacting with ACLs. You can mitigate this
508	                 performance issue using ``gsutil -m cp`` to perform parallel
509	                 copying. Note that this option only works if you have OWNER access
510	                 to all objects that are copied. If you want all objects in the
511	                 destination bucket to end up with the same ACL, you can avoid these
512	                 performance issues by setting a default object ACL on that bucket
513	                 instead of using ``cp -p``. See "gsutil help defacl".
514	
515	                 Note that it's not valid to specify both the ``-a`` and ``-p`` options
516	                 together.
517	
518	  -P             Enables POSIX attributes to be preserved when objects are
519	                 copied. ``gsutil cp`` copies fields provided by ``stat``. These fields
520	                 are the user ID of the owner, the group
521	                 ID of the owning group, the mode or permissions of the file, and
522	                 the access and modification time of the file. For downloads, these
523	                 attributes are only set if the source objects were uploaded
524	                 with this flag enabled.
525	
526	                 On Windows, this flag only sets and restores access time and
527	                 modification time. This is because Windows doesn't support
528	                 POSIX uid/gid/mode.
529	
530	  -R, -r         The ``-R`` and ``-r`` options are synonymous. They enable directories,
531	                 buckets, and bucket subdirectories to be copied recursively.
532	                 If you don't use this option for an upload, gsutil copies objects
533	                 it finds and skips directories. Similarly, if you don't
534	                 specify this option for a download, gsutil copies
535	                 objects at the current bucket directory level and skips subdirectories.
536	
537	  -s <class>     Specifies the storage class of the destination object. If not
538	                 specified, the default storage class of the destination bucket
539	                 is used. This option is not valid for copying to non-cloud destinations.
540	
541	  -U             Skips objects with unsupported object types instead of failing.
542	                 Unsupported object types include Amazon S3 objects in the GLACIER
543	                 storage class.
544	
545	  -v             Prints the version-specific URL for each uploaded object. You can
546	                 use these URLs to safely make concurrent upload requests, because
547	                 Cloud Storage refuses to perform an update if the current
548	                 object version doesn't match the version-specific URL. See
549	                 `generation numbers
550	                 <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/metadata#generation-number>`_
551	                 for more details.
552	
553	  -z <ext,...>   Applies gzip content-encoding to any file upload whose
554	                 extension matches the ``-z`` extension list. This is useful when
555	                 uploading files with compressible content such as .js, .css,
556	                 or .html files, because it reduces network bandwidth and storage
557	                 sizes. This can both improve performance and reduce costs.
558	
559	                 When you specify the ``-z`` option, the data from your files is
560	                 compressed before it is uploaded, but your actual files are
561	                 left uncompressed on the local disk. The uploaded objects
562	                 retain the ``Content-Type`` and name of the original files, but
563	                 have their ``Content-Encoding`` metadata set to ``gzip`` to
564	                 indicate that the object data stored are compressed on the
565	                 Cloud Storage servers and have their ``Cache-Control`` metadata
566	                 set to ``no-transform``.
567	
568	                 For example, the following command:
569	
570	                   gsutil cp -z html \\
571	                     cattypes.html tabby.jpeg gs://mycats
572	
573	                 does the following:
574	
575	                 - The ``cp`` command uploads the files ``cattypes.html`` and
576	                   ``tabby.jpeg`` to the bucket ``gs://mycats``.
577	                 - Based on the file extensions, gsutil sets the ``Content-Type``
578	                   of ``cattypes.html`` to ``text/html`` and ``tabby.jpeg`` to
579	                   ``image/jpeg``.
580	                 - The ``-z`` option compresses the data in the file ``cattypes.html``.
581	                 - The ``-z`` option also sets the ``Content-Encoding`` for
582	                   ``cattypes.html`` to ``gzip`` and the ``Cache-Control`` for
583	                   ``cattypes.html`` to ``no-transform``.
584	
585	                 Because the ``-z/-Z`` options compress data prior to upload, they
586	                 are not subject to the same compression buffer bottleneck that
587	                 can affect the ``-j/-J`` options.
588	
589	                 Note that if you download an object with ``Content-Encoding:gzip``,
590	                 gsutil decompresses the content before writing the local file.
591	
592	  -Z             Applies gzip content-encoding to file uploads. This option
593	                 works like the ``-z`` option described above, but it applies to
594	                 all uploaded files, regardless of extension.
595	
596	                 CAUTION: If some of the source files don't compress well, such
597	                 as binary data, using this option may result in files taking up
598	                 more space in the cloud than they would if left uncompressed.
599	
600	  --stet         If the STET binary can be found in boto or PATH, cp will
601	                 use the split-trust encryption tool for end-to-end encryption.
602	"""
603

44	<B>DESCRIPTION</B>

--------------------------------------------------
>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/notification.py:131
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
130	
131	_CREATE_DESCRIPTION = """
132	<B>CREATE</B>
133	  The create sub-command creates a notification config on a bucket, establishing
134	  a flow of event notifications from Cloud Storage to a Cloud Pub/Sub topic. As
135	  part of creating this flow, the create command also verifies that the
136	  destination Cloud Pub/Sub topic exists, creating it if necessary, and verifies
137	  that the Cloud Storage bucket has permission to publish events to that topic,
138	  granting the permission if necessary.
139	
140	  If a destination Cloud Pub/Sub topic is not specified with the -t flag, Cloud
141	  Storage chooses a topic name in the default project whose ID is the same as
142	  the bucket name. For example, if the default project ID specified is
143	  'default-project' and the bucket being configured is gs://example-bucket, the
144	  create command uses the Cloud Pub/Sub topic
145	  "projects/default-project/topics/example-bucket".
146	
147	  In order to enable notifications, your project's `Cloud Storage service agent
148	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/projects#service-accounts>`_ must have
149	  the IAM permission "pubsub.topics.publish". This command checks to see if the
150	  destination Cloud Pub/Sub topic grants the service agent this permission. If
151	  not, the create command attempts to grant it.
152	
153	  A bucket can have up to 100 total notification configurations and up to 10
154	  notification configurations set to trigger for a specific event.
155	
156	<B>CREATE EXAMPLES</B>
157	  Begin sending notifications of all changes to the bucket example-bucket
158	  to the Cloud Pub/Sub topic projects/default-project/topics/example-bucket:
159	
160	    gsutil notification create -f json gs://example-bucket
161	
162	  The same as above, but specifies the destination topic ID 'files-to-process'
163	  in the default project:
164	
165	    gsutil notification create -f json \\
166	      -t files-to-process gs://example-bucket
167	
168	  The same as above, but specifies a Cloud Pub/Sub topic belonging to the
169	  specific cloud project 'example-project':
170	
171	    gsutil notification create -f json \\
172	      -t projects/example-project/topics/files-to-process gs://example-bucket
173	
174	  Create a notification config that only sends an event when a new object
175	  has been created:
176	
177	    gsutil notification create -f json -e OBJECT_FINALIZE gs://example-bucket
178	
179	  Create a topic and notification config that only sends an event when
180	  an object beginning with "photos/" is affected:
181	
182	    gsutil notification create -p photos/ gs://example-bucket
183	
184	  List all of the notificationConfigs in bucket example-bucket:
185	
186	    gsutil notification list gs://example-bucket
187	
188	  Delete all notitificationConfigs for bucket example-bucket:
189	
190	    gsutil notification delete gs://example-bucket
191	
192	  Delete one specific notificationConfig for bucket example-bucket:
193	
194	    gsutil notification delete \\
195	      projects/_/buckets/example-bucket/notificationConfigs/1
196	
197	<B>OPTIONS</B>
198	  The create sub-command has the following options
199	
200	  -e        Specify an event type filter for this notification config. Cloud
201	            Storage only sends notifications of this type. You may specify this
202	            parameter multiple times to allow multiple event types. If not
203	            specified, Cloud Storage sends notifications for all event types.
204	            The valid types are:
205	
206	              OBJECT_FINALIZE - An object has been created.
207	              OBJECT_METADATA_UPDATE - The metadata of an object has changed.
208	              OBJECT_DELETE - An object has been permanently deleted.
209	              OBJECT_ARCHIVE - A live version of an object has become a
210	                noncurrent version.
211	
212	  -f        Specifies the payload format of notification messages. Must be
213	            either "json" for a payload matches the object metadata for the
214	            JSON API, or "none" to specify no payload at all. In either case,
215	            notification details are available in the message attributes.
216	
217	  -m        Specifies a key:value attribute that is appended to the set
218	            of attributes sent to Cloud Pub/Sub for all events associated with
219	            this notification config. You may specify this parameter multiple
220	            times to set multiple attributes.
221	
222	  -p        Specifies a prefix path filter for this notification config. Cloud
223	            Storage only sends notifications for objects in this bucket whose
224	            names begin with the specified prefix.
225	
226	  -s        Skips creation and permission assignment of the Cloud Pub/Sub topic.
227	            This is useful if the caller does not have permission to access
228	            the topic in question, or if the topic already exists and has the
229	            appropriate publish permission assigned.
230	
231	  -t        The Cloud Pub/Sub topic to which notifications should be sent. If
232	            not specified, this command chooses a topic whose project is your
233	            default project and whose ID is the same as the Cloud Storage bucket
234	            name.
235	
236	<B>NEXT STEPS</B>
237	  Once the create command has succeeded, Cloud Storage publishes a message to
238	  the specified Cloud Pub/Sub topic when eligible changes occur. In order to
239	  receive these messages, you must create a Pub/Sub subscription for your
240	  Pub/Sub topic. To learn more about creating Pub/Sub subscriptions, see `the
241	  Pub/Sub Subscriber Overview <https://cloud.google.com/pubsub/docs/subscriber>`_.
242	
243	  You can create a simple Pub/Sub subscription using the ``gcloud`` command-line
244	  tool. For example, to create a new subscription on the topic "myNewTopic" and
245	  attempt to pull messages from it, you could run:
246	
247	    gcloud beta pubsub subscriptions create --topic myNewTopic testSubscription
248	    gcloud beta pubsub subscriptions pull --auto-ack testSubscription
249	"""
250

251	_WATCHBUCKET_DESCRIPTION = """
252	<B>WATCHBUCKET</B>
253	  The watchbucket sub-command can be used to watch a bucket for object changes.
254	  A service account must be used when running this command.
255	
256	  The app_url parameter must be an HTTPS URL to an application that will be
257	  notified of changes to any object in the bucket.
258	
259	  The optional id parameter can be used to assign a unique identifier to the
260	  created notification channel. If not provided, a random UUID string is
261	  generated.
262	
263	  The optional token parameter can be used to validate notifications events.
264	  To do this, set this custom token and store it to later verify that
265	  notification events contain the client token you expect.
266	
267	<B>WATCHBUCKET EXAMPLES</B>
268	  Watch the bucket example-bucket for changes and send notifications to an
269	  application server running at example.com:
270	
271	    gsutil notification watchbucket https://example.com/notify \\
272	      gs://example-bucket
273	
274	  Assign identifier my-channel-id to the created notification channel:
275	
276	    gsutil notification watchbucket -i my-channel-id \\
277	      https://example.com/notify gs://example-bucket
278	
279	  Set a custom client token that is included with each notification event:
280	
281	    gsutil notification watchbucket -t my-client-token \\
282	      https://example.com/notify gs://example-bucket
283	"""

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/retention.py:78
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
77	
78	_SET_DESCRIPTION = """
79	<B>SET</B>
80	  You can configure a data retention policy for a Cloud Storage bucket that
81	  governs how long objects in the bucket must be retained. You can also lock the
82	  data retention policy, permanently preventing the policy from being reduced or
83	  removed. For more information, see `Retention policies and Bucket Lock
84	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/bucket-lock>`_.
85	
86	  The ``gsutil retention set`` command allows you to set or update the
87	  retention policy on one or more buckets.
88	
89	  To remove an unlocked retention policy from one or more
90	  buckets, use the ``gsutil retention clear`` command.
91	
92	  The ``set`` sub-command can set a retention policy with the following formats:
93	
94	<B>SET FORMATS</B>
95	  Formats for the ``set`` subcommand include:
96	
97	  <number>s
98	      Specifies retention period of <number> seconds for objects in this bucket.
99	
100	  <number>d
101	      Specifies retention period of <number> days for objects in this bucket.
102	
103	  <number>m
104	      Specifies retention period of <number> months for objects in this bucket.
105	
106	  <number>y
107	      Specifies retention period of <number> years for objects in this bucket.
108	
109	  GCS JSON API accepts retention periods as number of seconds. Durations provided
110	  in terms of days, months or years are converted to their rough equivalent
111	  values in seconds, using the following conversions:
112	
113	  - A month is considered to be 31 days or 2,678,400 seconds.
114	  - A year is considered to be 365.25 days or 31,557,600 seconds.
115	
116	  Retention periods must be greater than 0 and less than 100 years.
117	  Retention durations must be in only one form (seconds, days, months,
118	  or years), and not a combination of them.
119	
120	  Note that while it is possible to specify retention durations
121	  shorter than a day (using seconds), enforcement of such retention periods is not
122	  guaranteed. Such durations may only be used for testing purposes.
123	
124	<B>EXAMPLES</B>
125	  Setting a retention policy with a duration of 1 year on a bucket:
126	
127	    gsutil retention set 1y gs://my-bucket
128	
129	  Setting a retention policy with a duration of 36 months on a bucket:
130	
131	    gsutil retention set 36m gs://some-bucket
132	
133	  You can also provide a precondition on a bucket's metageneration in order to
134	  avoid potential race conditions. You can use gsutil's '-h' option to specify
135	  preconditions. For example, the following specifies a precondition that checks
136	  a bucket's metageneration before setting the retention policy on the bucket:
137	
138	    gsutil -h "x-goog-if-metageneration-match: 1" \\
139	      retention set 1y gs://my-bucket
140	"""
141	
142	_CLEAR_DESCRIPTION = """

>> Issue: [B824:url_found] url_found
   Severity: Medium   Confidence: Medium
   Location: /home/blue/PyPIAgent/Dataset/study/unzip_benign/gsutil-5.33/gsutil-5.33/gslib/commands/test.py:69
   More Info: https://bandit.readthedocs.io/en/latest/plugins/b824_url_found.html
68	<B>SYNOPSIS</B>
69	""" + _SYNOPSIS + """
70	
71	
72	<B>DESCRIPTION</B>
73	  The gsutil test command runs the gsutil unit tests and integration tests.
74	  The unit tests use an in-memory mock storage service implementation, while
75	  the integration tests send requests to the production service using the
76	  `preferred API
77	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/request-endpoints#gsutil>`_ set in the
78	  boto configuration file.
79	
80	  CAUTION: The ``test`` command creates test buckets and objects in your project.
81	  Force quitting the ``test`` command can leave behind stale buckets, objects,
82	  and HMAC keys in your project.
83	
84	  To run both the unit tests and integration tests, run the command with no
85	  arguments:
86	
87	    gsutil test
88	
89	  To run the unit tests only (which run quickly):
90	
91	    gsutil test -u
92	
93	  Tests run in parallel regardless of whether the top-level -m flag is
94	  present. To limit the number of tests run in parallel to 10 at a time:
95	
96	    gsutil test -p 10
97	
98	  To force tests to run sequentially:
99	
100	    gsutil test -p 1
101	
102	  To have sequentially-run tests stop running immediately when an error occurs:
103	
104	    gsutil test -f
105	
106	  To run tests for one or more individual commands add those commands as
107	  arguments. For example, the following command will run the cp and mv command
108	  tests:
109	
110	    gsutil test cp mv
111	
112	  To list available tests, run the test command with the -l argument:
113	
114	    gsutil test -l
115	
116	  The tests are defined in the code under the gslib/tests module. Each test
117	  file is of the format test_[name].py where [name] is the test name you can
118	  pass to this command. For example, running "gsutil test ls" would run the
119	  tests in "gslib/tests/test_ls.py".
120	
121	  You can also run an individual test class or function name by passing the
122	  test module followed by the class name and optionally a test name. For
123	  example, to run the an entire test class by name:
124	
125	    gsutil test naming.GsutilNamingTests
126	
127	  or an individual test function:
128	
129	    gsutil test cp.TestCp.test_streaming
130	
131	  You can list the available tests under a module or class by passing arguments
132	  with the -l option. For example, to list all available test functions in the
133	  cp module:
134	
135	    gsutil test -l cp
136	
137	  To output test coverage:
138	
139	    gsutil test -c -p 500
140	    coverage html
141	
142	  This will output an HTML report to a directory named 'htmlcov'.
143	
144	  Test coverage is compatible with v4.1 of the coverage module
145	  (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/coverage).
146	
147	
148	<B>OPTIONS</B>
149	  -b          Run tests against multi-regional US buckets. By default,
150	              tests run against regional buckets in us-central1.
151	
152	  -c          Output coverage information.
153	
154	  -f          Exit on first sequential test failure.
155	
156	  -l          List available tests.
157	
158	  -p N        Run at most N tests in parallel. The default value is %d.
159	
160	  -s          Run tests against S3 instead of GS.
161	
162	  -u          Only run unit tests.
163	""" % _DEFAULT_TEST_PARALLEL_PROCESSES)

76	
77	_DESCRIPTION = """
78	  Cloud Storage allows you to configure a bucket to behave like a static
79	  website when the bucket is accessed through a `custom domain
80	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/request-endpoints#custom-domains>`_.
81	  For example, if you set a ``main_page_suffix``, a subsequent GET bucket
82	  request through a custom domain serves the specified "main" page instead of
83	  performing the usual bucket listing. Similarly, if you set an ``error_page``,
84	  a subsequent GET object request through a custom domain for a non-existent
85	  object serves the specified error page instead of the standard Cloud Storage
86	  error.
87	
88	  Requests to a bucket through other `endpoints
89	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/request-endpoints>`_ are unaffected
90	  by the bucket's website configuration.
91	
92	  See `Static website examples and tips
93	  <https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/static-website>`_ for additional
94	  examples and information.
95	
96	  Notes:
97	
98	  1. Because the main page is only served when a bucket listing request is made
99	     via a custom domain endpoint, you can continue to use ``gsutil ls`` as you
100	     normally would for bucket listing.
101	
102	  2. The main_page_suffix applies to each subdirectory of the bucket. For
103	     example, with the main_page_suffix configured to be index.html, a GET
104	     request for ``http://www.example.com`` retrieves
105	     ``http://www.example.com/index.html`` but shows ``http://www.example.com`` as
106	     the URL to the requester, and a GET request for
107	     ``http://www.example.com/photos`` retrieves
108	     ``http://www.example.com/photos/index.html`` but shows ``http://www.example.com/photos``
109	     as the URL to the requester.
110	
111	  3. There is just one 404.html page. For example, a GET request for
112	     ``http://www.example.com/photos/missing`` retrieves
113	     ``http://www.example.com/404.html``, not
114	     ``http://www.example.com/photos/404.html``.
115	
116	  The web command has two sub-commands:
117	""" + _SET_DESCRIPTION + _GET_DESCRIPTION
118
